The paper focuses on natural language processing tasks, specifically semantic matching of sentences, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. The use of convolutional neural networks also suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions that the proposed models require no prior knowledge on language, indicating that it could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The mention of pooling and layer-by-layer composition suggests that it could also belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. Finally, the empirical study on a variety of matching tasks suggests that it could also belong to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category.
